  "prompt": "What is an expression analogous to rest in peace in Hinduism?",
  "response": "In Hinduism, an expression analogous to \"rest in peace\" is **\"Om Shanti\"** (\u0950 \u0936\u093e\u0928\u094d\u0924\u093f). This phrase is commonly used to wish peace for the departed soul. \"Shanti\" means peace, and \"Om\" is a sacred sound and spiritual symbol in Hinduism, representing the ultimate reality or consciousness. The phrase \"Om Shanti\" is often repeated three times to signify peace in the body, mind, and soul.\n\nAnother expression used is **\"Atma Ko Sadgati Prapt Ho\"** (\u0906\u0924\u094d\u092e\u093e \u0915\u094b \u0938\u0926\u094d\u0917\u0924\u093f \u092a\u094d\u0930\u093e\u092a\u094d\u0924 \u0939\u094b), which means \"May the soul attain liberation (moksha).\" This reflects the Hindu belief in the cycle of rebirth and the ultimate goal of liberation from it.\n\nBoth expressions are used in prayers and rituals to honor the deceased and wish them peace and liberation.",
